				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>While I can&#8217;t say that older works are not represented, there are some pretty big gaps in the historiography. Royster, Shy, Ira Gruber, William B. Wilcox, David Syrett, all produced work still worth reading. Royster and Shy in particular helped transform the study of the conflict back in the 1970s and 80s. The list is tilted toward what is still in print, I suppose, which makes sense for a popular audience.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

