				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>You&#8217;re absolutely right, Ruth. We&#8217;d love a more diverse roster of writers and enthusiastically welcome all to submit for publication. We don&#8217;t recruit authors so our make-up is almost entirely determined by those who discover our site and submit articles for consideration. We reject submissions if they fall too far outside our editorial scope or don&#8217;t meet our high research/narrative standards.</p>
<p>That said, if you&#8217;re interested in contributing or know any exceptional writers, please send them our way. We&#8217;d gladly accept social or cultural histories as long as the primary focus is the American Revolution. </p>
<p>Thanks again for commenting! One of the most rewarding parts of this journal is the conversations that take place after the article. Oh, and if you&#8217;re interested, here are a few of our favorite past articles that deal more with the social/cultural side of the Revolution.</p>
<p>+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2016/10/major-andre-popularizes-revolutionary-events/">Major Andre Popularizes Revolutionary Events</a>&#8221; by Michelle Porter<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2016/08/revolutionary-war-olympics-games-founders-played/">Revolutionary War Olympics: The Games Our Founders Played</a>&#8221; by Joshua Shepherd<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2016/11/society-auction-coffee-house-culture-occupied-new-york/">Society at Auction: Coffee-house Culture in Occupied New York</a>&#8221; by Jonathan Bayer<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2015/11/fever/">Fever</a>&#8221; by Kim Burdick<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2015/08/domestic-disputes-public-announcements-of-private-affairs/">Domestic Disputes: Public Announcements of Private Affairs</a>&#8221; by Don N. Hagist<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2015/02/top-10-revolutionary-war-newspapers/">Top 10 Revolutionary War Newspapers</a>&#8221; by Carol Sue Humphrey<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2015/02/how-paul-reveres-ride-was-published-and-censored-in-1775/">How Paul Revere&#8217;s Ride was Published and Censored in 1775</a>&#8221; by Todd Andrlik<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2014/06/an-elegant-dinner-with-general-washington-at-valley-forge-headquarters/">An Elegant Dinner with General Washington at Valley Forge HQ</a> by Nancy K. Loane<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2014/11/peggy-left-the-party-and-you-wont-believe-what-happened-next/">Peggy Left the Party, and You Won&#8217;t Believe What Happened Next</a>&#8221; by Don N. Hagist<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/12/washingtons-five-books/">Washington&#8217;s Five Books</a>&#8221; by J. L. Bell<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/11/top-10-marriages-gone-bad/">Top 10 Marriages Gone Bad</a>&#8221; by Don N. Hagist<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2014/06/william-lee-and-oney-judge-a-look-at-george-washington-slavery/">William Lee &#038; Oney Judge: A Look at George Washington &#038; Slavery</a> by Mary V. Thompson<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/07/feeding-the-slaves/">Feeding the Slaves</a>&#8221; and &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/05/family-dinner-soup-molasses-bread-jeffersons-meringues/">Family Dinner</a>&#8221; by Lars D. H. Hedbor<br />
+ &#8220;<a href="https://allthingsliberty.com/2013/03/the-role-of-dancing/">The Role of Dancing</a>&#8221; by Pamela Murrow</p>
