				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>&#8220;John Adams&#8221; by McCullough (listed) is a very good book. But I&#8217;m finishing up the two-volume biography of Adams by Page Smith (published 1962 and 1963), and I think Smith delves so much more deeply into his subject than does McCullough. Additionally, Smith&#8217;s treatment of Adams in the time leading up to, not to mention during, the Revolution makes for some fascinating reading. It is intellectually difficult to treat Adams separately from the Revolution (and vice-versa). He was, in so many ways, such an important actor throughout the entirety of the struggle.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

